00:00:57,500 --> 00:01:05,900
English learners with years of training have trouble with these little words and for good reason. The

8
00:01:05,900 --> 00:01:14,140
rules differ from language to language, making it tricky to know when to use them. But don't worry,

9
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:23,560
the good news is that some kinds of nouns do not require articles in speech or writing. This idea

10
00:01:23,560 --> 00:01:33,640
is often called the zero article. The term zero article itself is not very important. It is just

11
00:01:33,640 --> 00:01:42,920
a way of saying no article is used. There are many kinds of nouns that are not preceded by

12
00:01:42,920 --> 00:01:52,220
articles in English. Other nouns get no article only in some kinds of statements, such as

13
00:01:52,220 --> 00:02:02,200
generalizations. To begin, we do not use articles before plural nouns and non-count nouns when making

14
00:02:02,200 --> 00:02:11,580
generalizations. A generalization is a broad statement or an idea that can be applied to a

15
00:02:11,580 --> 00:02:21,480
whole group of people or things. As you may know, a plural noun is the form of a word that relates

16
00:02:21,480 --> 00:02:31,940
to more than one person or thing, like apples, dogs, telephones, and children. Let's listen to

17
00:02:31,940 --> 00:02:40,100
an example of a generalization with plural nouns. Dogs are much more playful than cats.

18
00:02:41,780 --> 00:02:49,920
This is a very broad statement applied to two groups of animals, so we do not use articles.

19
00:02:51,480 --> 00:03:00,640
We do, however, use articles with plural nouns in specific statements. Here is an example for comparison.

20
00:03:02,300 --> 00:03:10,160
The dogs at the doggy park are very playful. The speaker is talking of specific dogs,

21
00:03:10,840 --> 00:03:18,160
the ones at the doggy park, so the article the is used before the plural noun dogs.

22
00:03:19,460 --> 00:03:28,040
Now let's move on to non-count nouns. You may remember from an earlier program that a non-count

23
00:03:28,040 --> 00:03:38,800
noun is a noun that we usually do not count, so it does not appear in plural form. Non-count nouns

24
00:03:38,800 --> 00:03:49,240
include materials like gold, substances like water and fire, abstract things like music and justice,

25
00:03:50,040 --> 00:03:58,780
and some other things. Generalizations with non-count nouns are not preceded by articles.

26
00:03:59,860 --> 00:04:08,460
Let's hear an example. I like listening to music while I exercise. The person is not

27
00:04:08,460 --> 00:04:15,760
speaking of specific music. They are saying they enjoy the general act of listening to music

28
00:04:15,760 --> 00:04:26,060
as they exercise. For comparison, here's a specific statement. The music at the show last night was

29
00:04:26,060 --> 00:04:34,080
too loud. The person is speaking of specific music, the music at the show last night.

30
00:04:35,040 --> 00:04:45,200
So the article the appears before the non-count noun music. The zero article also applies to other

31
00:04:45,200 --> 00:04:52,820
kinds of nouns. For instance, we normally do not put an article in front of a proper noun,

32
00:04:53,360 --> 00:05:02,280
a word or group of words that name a specific person, place, or thing. Proper nouns are easy

33
00:05:02,280 --> 00:05:10,320
